<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-09-30T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-09-30T18:00:00-05:00" n="96" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d96">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01/9–2349: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Consul General at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-09-30T18:00:00-05:00">September
                                    30, 1949—6 p. m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>337. Reurtel 779 September 23. Secy and Un Secy made following points re
                            question recog: <list>
                                <label>1.</label>
                                <item>Time for decision when or if recog has not yet arrived as
                                    central Chi Comm govt not yet officially established.</item>
                                <pb facs="0103" n="93" xml:id="pg_93"/>
                                <label>2.</label>
                                <item>Dept will undertake closest consultation with Cong prior
                                    taking any action re recog Chi Comm regime.</item>
                                <label>3.</label>
                                <item>Dept desires keep in close touch, and if feasible concert
                                    efforts, with all concerned friendly nations on major Chi
                                    questions, including problem recog.</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>For urinfo only, early recog by US highly unlikely. Likewise Dept’s info
                            indicates Brit Govt will not be hasty in according recog.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Webb</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>